      "topic": "Data Analytics - Pivot Tables and Data Visualization",
      "question": "A fraud examiner is analyzing employee expense reports for a company with 500 employees across 5 regions. The data includes employee ID, region, expense category (meals, travel, lodging, other), amount, and date. The examiner wants to identify unusual patterns that may indicate fraudulent expense claims.\n\nWhich of the following data analysis techniques would be MOST effective for identifying potential red flags in this dataset?",
      "options": [
        "A. Create a pivot table summarizing total expenses by employee and region, then calculate the mean and standard deviation to identify outliers who claim expenses significantly above the average.",
        "B. Sort the entire dataset by amount in descending order and manually review the top 50 highest expense claims for supporting documentation.",
        "C. Use a line chart to visualize expense trends over time for each of the five regions to identify seasonal variations.",
        "D. Apply a simple filter to identify all expenses over $1,000 and forward these to management for approval verification."
      ],
      "correct_answer": "A",
      "explanation": "Option A is the most effective approach because pivot tables allow the fraud examiner to efficiently aggregate and summarize large datasets by multiple dimensions (employee and region). By calculating statistical measures (mean and standard deviation), the examiner can systematically identify outliers that deviate significantly from normal patterns, which is a key fraud detection technique. This approach is scalable, systematic, and allows for comparative analysis across different segments.\n\nOption B is inefficient and may miss fraudulent patterns that involve many smaller amounts or claims that are strategically kept below attention thresholds. Option C focuses only on time trends by region and would miss employee-level anomalies. Option D uses an arbitrary threshold without statistical basis and may generate many false positives while missing fraudulent claims just below $1,000.",
      "topic_code": "S2D11",
